ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic H2 production performance was tested under visible light (λ ≥ 420 nm). Firstly, the H2 production rate of ultrathin CN nanosheets can reach 1.57 mmol g−1 h−1, which is about 7.26 times that of traditional bulk g-C3N4 (Fig. S1). More importantly, after loading NCDs on CN nanosheets, the photocatalytic performances of NCDs(x)/CN were dramatically enhanced. Among them, the photocatalyst loaded with 0.5 wt% NCDs exhibited the highest hydrogen production rate (5.21 mmol g−1 h−1), which was about 3.32 times that of CN nanosheets (Fig. 7
                     ). The results proved that depositing a small amount of NCDs on CN nanosheets can markedly boost the photocatalytic H2 production performance. Note that the apparent quantum efficiency (AQE) can achieve 18.37% at 420 nm (Fig. 8
                     a). And the AQE at 550 nm can still reach 0.98%, implying that the loading of NCDs can improve light utilization, thereby enhancing H2 production performance. The photocatalytic hydrogen production performance of as-prepared NCDs(0.5)/CN is also superior to that of many other reported catalysts (Table S5). To research the stability of the catalysts, the cycling performance of NCDs(0.5)/CN was carried out (Fig. 8b). After four cycles, although the hydrogen evolution rate fluctuated slightly, it still remained at a high level. In addition, the PL and FTIR spectra of the NCDs(0.5)/CN before and after the reaction are basically the same (Fig. 8c and d), demonstrating that the standout stability and photocatalytic activity of NCDs(0.5)/CN.
